        "Quilted": {
            "stats": {
                "crush": 3,
                "pierce": 2,
                "slash": 4,
                "durability": 32,
                "mobility": -1
            },
            "description": "The workhorse armour of the medieval world. A thick jacket of linen or wool, quilted and stuffed with wool, horsehair, rags, or tow. The dense padding absorbs and disperses blunt impact remarkably well — arguably better than most armours except plate — and the layered cloth resists slashing cuts. Its weakness is piercing: a strong thrust will force the point through the fibres. It was worn alone by poorer soldiers and universally worn beneath mail and plate by everyone else. Fast, cheap, and effective, the gambeson was the foundation of medieval personal defence.",
