        "Mail": {
            "stats": {
                "crush": 2,
                "pierce": 6,
                "slash": 7,
                "durability": 105,
                "mobility": -2
            },
            "description": "Thousands of interlocking iron or steel rings, each passing through four neighbours, forming a flexible metal fabric. Mail is outstanding against cutting and slashing attacks — a blade cannot find purchase on the rings and simply skates off — and the dense ring structure resists many thrusting points. Its critical weakness is blunt trauma: the flexible structure has nothing to stop force transferring directly through the rings into the body beneath. A mace or warhammer blow against mail may not penetrate the rings at all, yet still shatter bone. Mail was ubiquitous throughout the European Middle Ages and was always worn over a padded gambeson to offset this weakness.",
