        "Plate": {
            "stats": {
                "crush": 8,
                "pierce": 6,
                "slash": 7,
                "durability": 160,
                "mobility": -3
            },
            "description": "The pinnacle of medieval European armour craft. Large, carefully shaped and fitted steel plates covering the entire body, articulated at the joints with smaller lames and rivets. A well-made harness of plate spreads blunt impact across a large rigid surface, making it the best possible defence against crushing weapons — the maximum on our scale. Slashing attacks glance off curved surfaces. Pierce is the one remaining vulnerability: a rondel dagger, bodkin-tipped arrow, or estoc thrust can find the gaps at the armpits, visor, and joints, or drive through thinner sections with enough force. Full plate was extraordinarily expensive, requiring months of skilled labour, and was the exclusive preserve of wealthy knights and nobility.",
            "failure": "Plates deform and crack at articulation points; catastrophic failure rare.",
